{"id":"1904.06547","submitter":"Michael Margaliot","authors":"Rami Katz and Michael Margaliot and Emilia Fridman","title":"Entrainment to Subharmonic Trajectories in Oscillatory Discrete-Time\n  Systems","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A matrix $A$ is called totally positive (TP) if all its minors are positive,\nand totally nonnegative (TN) if all its minors are nonnegative. A square matrix\n$A$ is called oscillatory if it is TN and some power of $A$ is TP. A linear\ntime-varying system is called an oscillatory discrete-time system (ODTS) if the\nmatrix defining its evolution at each time $k$ is oscillatory. We analyze the\nproperties of $n$-dimensional time-varying nonlinear discrete-time systems\nwhose variational system is an ODTS, and show that they have a well-ordered\nbehavior. More precisely, if the nonlinear system is time-varying and\n$T$-periodic then any trajectory either leaves any compact set or converges to\nan $(n-1)T$-periodic trajectory, that is, a subharmonic trajectory. These\nresults hold for any dimension $n$. The analysis of such systems requires\nestablishing that a line integral of the Jacobian of the nonlinear system is an\noscillatory matrix. This is non-trivial, as the sum of two oscillatory matrices\nis not necessarily oscillatory, and this carries over to integrals. We derive\nseveral new sufficient conditions guaranteeing that the line integral of a\nmatrix is oscillatory, and demonstrate how this yields interesting classes of\ndiscrete-time nonlinear systems that admit a well-ordered behavior.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 13 Apr 2019 13:33:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-04-16"}
